Class Vehicle

java.lang.Object
com.iunera.jsonldjava.schemaorg.metadatatypes.Thing
com.iunera.jsonldjava.schemaorg.metadatatypes.Product
com.iunera.jsonldjava.schemaorg.metadatatypes.Vehicle
Direct Known Subclasses:
Car
public class Vehicle extends Product
A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.

    • fuelConsumption

      public QuantitativeValue fuelConsumption
      The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).
      • Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km. Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
      • Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
      • Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.

    • vehicleConfiguration

      public String vehicleConfiguration
      A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.

      The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.

    • numberOfForwardGearsQuantitativeValue

    • fuelEfficiency

      public QuantitativeValue fuelEfficiency
      The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).
      • Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter. Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
      • Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
      • Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.

    • vehicleModelDate

      public Date vehicleModelDate
      The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

    • vehicleInteriorColor

      public String vehicleInteriorColor
      The color or color combination of the interior of the vehicle.

    • cargoVolume

      public QuantitativeValue cargoVolume
      The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume. Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet Note: You can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.

    • vehicleEngine

      public EngineSpecification vehicleEngine
      Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.
